sec.p:
DFIG employs vector ($d q$) control for effective power management. Vector control entails the precise configuration of the stator flux and electromagnetic torque within a spatial framework, alongside the regulation of the $d q$ axis rotor currents. The coordinate system is aligned with the stator flow vector's rotation. The control method employs sine-PWM integrated with third harmonic injection [11]. The Park transformation serves as an important mathematical formulation for analysing DFIG, initiating the control modelling methodology. To calculate the rotor current in the $d$ and $q$ axes, it is essential to ascertain the rotor location $\theta_{r}$. The position of rotor angle $\theta_{r}$ is given as,
\begin{equation*}
\theta_{r}=\theta_{1}^{*}-\frac{\pi}{2}-\theta_{m} \tag{1}
\end{equation*}
Where $\theta_{1}^{*}$ represents the grid position determined from phase-locked loop (PLL) and $\theta_{m}$ denotes the position of the DFIG. The calculation of rotor current components can be performed using $i_{r}$ and $\theta_{r}$ to $i_{d r}$ and $i_{q r}$, as illustrated in Fig. 2. The rotor speed reference is established through an optimal tip speed ratio (OTSR) algorithm, enabling the maximum power extraction from the incoming wind speed. The electromagnetic torque ($T_{e m}$) and stator reactive power ($Q_{s}$) are influenced by the $d q$ axis rotor currents ($i_{d r}$ and $i_{q r}$) [12]. The generation of $T_{e m}$ is articulated as follows
\begin{equation*}
T_{e m}=-\frac{3}{2} * p * \frac{l_{m}}{l_{s}} *\left|\psi_{s}\right\vert * i_{q r} \tag{2}
\end{equation*}

Fig. 1.

Configuration of multi-mode ac/dc microgrid.

The $Q_{s}$ consumed by the stator of the DFIG and synchronous speed are as follows:
\begin{gather*}
Q_{s}=-\frac{3}{2} * \omega_{s} * \frac{l_{m}}{l_{s}} *\left|\psi_{s}\right\vert *\left(i_{d r}-\frac{\left|\vec{\psi}_{s}\right\vert}{l_{m}}\right) \tag{3}\\
\omega_{s}=\frac{2 * \pi * f}{p} \tag{4}
\end{gather*}

The grid-side control of the MG includes renewable energy sources, battery systems, and non linear loads. The presence of unbalanced or balanced non-linear demands in three-phase grid, coupled with the variability of solar and wind energy generation, may adversely affect the power quality of the grid. Achieving optimal PQ requires addressing unexpected disturbances effectively. Adaptive filters are employed to achieve this objective. The process of stochastic gradient descent exemplifies how numerous adaptive filters modify their weights which is illustrated as:
\begin{equation*}
w(n+1)=w(n)+\varepsilon \nabla_{w(n)} J(n) \tag{5}
\end{equation*}
Where $\mathrm{w}(\mathrm{n})$ is the equivalent weight, $J(n)$ is the cost function at nth iteration respectively. The steady-state error and tracking speed depend on the two variables $\varepsilon$ and $\nabla_{w(n)} J(n)$ respectively. The suggested VSS Q-Newton adaptive filter's weight update mechanism is comparable to the adaptive quasi-LMS/Newton approach, which makes use of the inverse correlation matrix [14]. In contrast to other methods, this methodology uses a regularised version of the matrix inverse estimate that is updated continuously throughout time. This change lowers the steady-state error by enhancing the initial convergence process and lessening the impact of the matrix inverse during the convergence phase. Fig. 4 shows the block diagram representation of VSS-Q-Newton based GSC control.

Fig. 3.

Block diagram of bes and spv array

The formula for adjusting the weight vector in the proposed VSS-Q-Newton algorithm is expressed as:
\begin{equation*}
w_{n l a a b c}(n+1)=w_{n l a a b c}(n)+\mu(n) u_{a b c}(n) e_{a b c}(n) \Phi_{a b c}(n) \tag{6}
\end{equation*}
Where $\mu(n)$ denotes the Variable Step Size (VSS) and is adapted using the following rule:
\begin{equation*}
\mu(n)=\beta \mu(n-1)+\varsigma \exp [-\mu(n-1)] \mu(n-1) \tag{7}
\end{equation*}
Where $0<\beta<1$ and $0<\varsigma<1$ are the forgetting factors to adjust the step size $\mu(n)$. In this adaptation rule, $\beta$ (set to 0.98) acts as a decaying factor for the previous step-size, ensuring smooth adaptation. ✓ (set to 0.005) controls the influence of the exponential term, which is vital for balancing rapid convergence during transient phases with a low steady-state error. The initial step-size, $\mu(0)$, was empirically determined and set to 0.1, providing an appropriate starting point for effective adaptation across various operational conditions. The $u_{a b c}(n)$ denotes the three-phase unit-templates respectively and is derived using the phase voltages ($v_{g a}, v_{g b}$, and $v_{g c}$) and voltage peak value ($V_{g t}^{*}$) at the PCC which is given as,
\begin{equation*}
V_{g t}^{*}=\sqrt{\frac{2}{3}\left(v_{g a}^{2}+v_{g b}^{2}+v_{g c}^{2}\right)} \tag{8}
\end{equation*}

Fig. 4.

Representation of grid side control using vss q-newton algorithm

The unit template $u_{a b c}(n)$ is calculated as,
\begin{equation*}
u(n)_{a b c}=\frac{V_{g, a b c}}{V_{g t}^{*}} \tag{9}
\end{equation*}
Where, $e_{a b c}(n)$ denotes the error between the current drawn by the non-linear load ($i_{\text {nlabc }}$) and the computed weight equivalent of the current drawn by the nonlinear load, it is given as,
\begin{equation*}
e_{a b c}(n)=i_{n l a b c}(n)-w_{n l a b c}(n) * u_{a b c}(n) \tag{10}
\end{equation*}

$\phi_{a b c}(n)$ represents a time-varying regularized matrix inverse. It is a regularisation factor aimed at enhancing noise robustness and improving convergence performance. It is denoted as:
\begin{equation*}
\begin{array}{r}
\Phi_{a b c}(n)=\frac{1}{1-\lambda}\left\{\phi_{a b c}(n-1)\right. \\
\left.-\frac{\phi_{a b c}(n-1) u_{a b c}(n)^{*} u_{a b c}^{t}(n) \phi_{a b c}(n-1)}{u_{a b c}^{t}(n) \phi_{a b c}(n-1)^{*} u_{a b c}(n)^{*} \frac{1-\lambda}{\lambda}}\right\}
\end{array} \tag{11}
\end{equation*}
Where $\lambda$ helps control the rate at which the inverse matrix estimate adapts. The three-phase equivalent weight of the current drawn by the nonlinear load is stated as $w_{\text {nlabc }}(n)$. The net weight equivalent ($w_{\text {pnet }}$) of the reference grid current ($i_{g a b c}$) is as follows:
\begin{equation*}
w_{p n e t}=w_{n l a b c}-w_{w i n d F F}+w_{p v F F}+w_{p B M S} \tag{12}
\end{equation*}
Where $w_{\text {windFF }}, w_{P V F F}$ and $w_{F F B M S}$ are feed-forward terms (FF) of wind, SPV and battery. Consequently, the power fluctuations in the SPV array, DFIG-based WECS, and battery during charging and discharging contribute to variations in the power quality of the microgrid, which in turn causes variations in the $i_{g a b c}$. To address this situation and improve robustness and efficiency, FF terms incorporating battery, photovoltaic, and wind power is utilised, as expressed as,
\begin{align*}
W_{D F I G, F F} & =\frac{2 *\left(P_{D F I G a}+P_{D F I G b}\right)}{3 V_{g t}^{*}} \tag{13}\\
W_{D F I G, F F} & =\frac{2 *\left(P_{D F I G a}+P_{D F I G b}\right)}{3 V_{g t}^{*}} \tag{14}
\end{align*}

The FF term of the battery regulates its charging and discharging processes. The FF term is upheld at full discharge by subtracting the battery's rated ampere-hour (A-h) capacity once the state of charge (SoC) exceeds 80 %. Incorporating the battery's rated ampere-hour (A-h) capacity maintains the final discharge duration when the state of charge (SoC) falls below 30 %. It removes half of the $\mathrm{A}-\mathrm{h}$ capacity from the FF term. These are the conditions under which the battery is neither forcefully charged nor discharged. To induce charging, conditions of state of charge below 30 % are applied to the battery, while for discharging, conditions above 80 % are utilised. The reference grid current ($i_{\text {gabc }}^{*}$) is as follows:
\begin{equation*}
i_{g a}^{*}=w_{\text {pnet }} * u_{p a}; i_{g b}^{*}=w_{\text {pnet }} * u_{p b}; i_{g c}^{*}=w_{\text {pnet }} * u_{p c} \tag{15}
\end{equation*}
